DENGUE - USA (TEXAS), MEXICO (COAHUILA) (02)
******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
[see: Dengue - USA (Texas), Mexico (Coahuila) 990818161131]
Date: Tue, 24 Aug 1999 23:32:01 -0400
From: "Marjorie P. Pollack" <pollackmp@mindspring.com>
& Clyde Markon <docmarkon@worldnet.att.net>
Source: The Dallas News (AP) 21 Aug 1999 [edited]
http://www.dallasnews.com/texas_southwest/0821tsw4dengue.htm

In the last 2 weeks, 15 people have been treated for dengue fever, spurring
health officials to step up efforts to rid the city of mosquitoes that
spread the disease.
Dengue fever is a viral illness spread by the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito.
Symptoms include high fever, severe headaches, joint and muscle pain,
nausea, vomiting and a skin rash.
"There's never been an outbreak of dengue fever [in Laredo] of this
significance to our knowledge," Jerry Robinson, health department director,
said Friday.
Aross the river from Laredo, in Nuevo Laredo, Mexico, 106 cases of dengue
fever have been confirmed, Mr. Robinson said, but the number is thought to
be much higher.
The local health department is waiting for the Texas Department of Health to
confirm its test results. As of Friday, two cases had been verified, said
Texas Department of Health spokesman Doug McBride.
Laredo has fewer cases than its sister city [in Mexico] because of an active
insecticide campaign, fewer containers kept outside and screens that keep
the mosquitoes out of homes.
