[Re:
"Does any knowledgeable reader wish to stick her/his neck out and forecast,
given recent & projected weather conditions, whether this presages an
epidemic in Texas? - Mod.JW]"
[1]
Date: Fri, 20 Aug 1999 12:59:19 -0400
From: jlentino <JLentino@compuserve.com>

This morning on the weather forecast, the station took time to air a report
from the national weather service, in which they were reporting that this
year may be the worst in 30 years for hurricanes. While I don't recall the
exact numbers, I think 49 tropical storms are predicted, 11 I think are
suppose to become hurricanes, one is predicted for landfall E. Coast (this I
do recall), and I think 3 were expected to hit the gulf coast.
There is one disturbance sitting on the Yucatan Peninsular that is expected
to create a tropical storm later into the day/week as it moves to the base
of Texas.
Given this information, mosquito populations could expand over wide areas.
I have never known the critters to be in short supply in Lubbock, however
could the winds carry the things this far north, or spread them throughout
the valley, and up in to the big thicket area?
--
J Lentino
m. battle Sgt USAR
<JLentino@compuserve.com>
